SIMPLE: piety
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Piety
<hw>Pi"e*ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>pi⟦eacute⟧t⟦eacute⟧</ets>; cf. It. <ets>piet⟦agrave⟧</ets>; both
fr. L. <ets>pietas</ets> piety, fr. <ets>pius</ets> pious. See
<er>Pious</er>, and cf. <er>Pity</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Veneration or reverence of the Supreme Being, and love of his
character; loving obedience to the will of God, and earnest devotion to
his service.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Piety</qex> is the only proper and adequate relief of
decaying man.</q> <rj><qau>Rambler.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Duty; dutifulness; filial reverence and devotion;
affectionate reverence and service shown toward parents, relatives,
benefactors, country, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Conferred upon me for the <qex>piety</qex>⟦br⟧
Which to my country I was judged to have shown.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Religion; sanctity; devotion; godliness;
holiness. See <er>Religion</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Piewipe</ent>⟦br⟧
